The paper deals with the problem of generating accurate probabilistic predictions for uncertain behavior of other road users in highly interactive driving scenarios, which is a core problem in the field of autonomous driving. The paper proposes a unified framework to homogenize the problem formulation, representation simplification, and evaluation metric for various prediction methods, such as probabilistic graphical models (PGM), neural networks (NN) and inverse reinforcement learning (IRL). This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO), Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI), and Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of computer vision (cs.CV) techniques for generating probabilistic predictions. Additionally, the paper proposes a fatality-aware metric to evaluate the consequences of inaccurate predictions, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
